        Three-stage retention pipeline replaces all-or-nothing direct purge:
          audit row -> (trash with ttl) --restore in window-->|
                            |                                 |
                            | ttl elapsed                     |
                            v                                 v
                    sweep_expired ---|                  audit row back
                                     v
                            arion_firstnet_undo_audit_purge_log
                            (existing slot-12 forensic chain table)

        Default TTL = 30 days. Restoring before TTL is free (no chain row
        — original audit id preserved). After TTL, sweep_firstnet_undo_
        audit_trash_expired marks the trash row expired_ms=now, physically
        retires the live audit row, and writes a per-trash summary into
        the purge-log table with scope_filter='trash_sweep'. The trash
        row itself is NEVER physically deleted — a forensic question
        ("did anyone touch audit row 8421 between dates X and Y?") can
        still answer YES years later.
        4 new methods on PrecinctGeofenceRegistry:
          trash_firstnet_undo_audit(audit_id, *, operator, reason,
